message_1: In higher-order logic, if we define a set of natural numbers as a function which denotes the length of the sequence of natural numbers, how many elements are in the set {(n,m) | n, m in N and n + m = 10}?
message_2:
To find the number of elements in the set {(n,m) | n, m in N and n + m = 10}, we need to find the number of pairs (n, m) of natural numbers that satisfy the condition n + m = 10.

We can list out the possible pairs:

(1, 9)
(2, 8)
(3, 7)
(4, 6)
(5, 5)
(6, 4)
(7, 3)
(8, 2)
(9, 1)

There are 9 pairs of natural numbers (n, m) that satisfy the condition n + m = 10. Therefore, there are 9 elements in the set.
